##Germany's 'quarantine' diary | | outside, Sun shines on Hanman Street, shelves sold out

| | leaf wind

Well we are all in the mood for a melody,

And you've got us all feeling alright.

I went back to Munich this weekend from London on business. If you're out on the streets, Londoners insist on an English style of "mind over mouth" -- as if a paper toilet paper broke your head and you couldn't even wear a mask until you reached the airport, a high-risk area. A month ago, you might have been scolded for wearing a mask at the airport. This time, about a quarter of our friends from all over the world were wearing N95s on the flight back to Germany. I don't know if the person who scolded the most secretly hoarded the most. Out of Habit (laziness) , I usually wait until the last one on the plane, and successfully observed a European friend without a mask spray his Huawei before and after three times alcohol.

I admit that I was one of those backward people who hated wearing masks and finally gave in on the flight. I've always felt that an effective mask can be a quarantine, like a lock because it protects me from viruses, and it also prevents me from running around in it and infecting people. Before I fell asleep, I saw the purser reminding the person next to me to fasten their seat belts. He was wearing a mask, too, and it was bigger than my N95. I think he unbuckled his seat belt because it felt a bit puffy -- as if he was wearing a higher quality mask than the Chinese next to him. The outbreak has changed the chain of daily disdain, and consumerist values have been quietly shuffled.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
There are not many people in Munich street. Maybe they went to the park to bask in the sunshine when the weather was too good.

The plane landed at the Empty Munich airport. Germany secretly wants to infect most people, too, but Merkl is not as big a mouth as Boris. The attitude of ordinary Germans against the disease is also in a tangle of anxiety and disdain. It's easy to get beaten up if you write too abstractly, for example: the Customs Guy who checked my passport was about twenty-four, had the self possessed look of a young German, and certainly couldn't wear a mask, which was dismissive. His gradually affected posture as I approached, the opening of the two-centimeter window and the mere clinking of his passport with two (gloved) fingers, was anxiety.

Munich weather is very good, residents have to take the children out in the sun. High school students who had nothing to do because their schools were closed also wandered the streets like vagrants. No one's wearing masks, and neither am I.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sometimes I have to lament the German construction level is generally higher, ordinary residential balcony in the sun also has a little taste of Bauhaus.

Nationality is an illusory concept. However, the arrival of the epidemic, it has to be felt that people in different countries have an irreconcilable attitude towards life and death. If I think of wearing a mask as an act of responsibility to others, the Germans don't seem to mind this social responsibility, as if they don't feel like doing it, and in fact they don't mind being infected either. It could be said that this is irresponsible for the small group of people who pay attention to prevention. However, the German mind is remarkably consistent, in a sense, it's not hard to understand why Hegel thought that the Kingdom of Prussia of the time had achieved the ideal of a society in which the state and the individual were in complete harmony. I went out because one of my favorite German shower gel brands wasn't available online, and I walked into the supermarket and was struck by the paradoxical double reality: The Sun was shining down on the street, and the toilet paper kitchen shelves were empty, the only remaining two bottles of body wash were swiped by a creepy Chinese guy with glasses.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The shelves in London are so clean anyway.

Go Home, wash your hands, wipe your phone. I'm going back to London tomorrow, and I've always thought the idea that my country could save me was an illusion. The most panicky people and the most disdainful people have no epidemic to hit the wall, people to the end can only rely on themselves. I also have a couple of N95s in my bag for the flight, a bottle of hand sanitizer, a bag of disinfectant paper towels and two new body washes. They say you can't be too afraid to die, or too afraid to die.
